\f + \fr 10:1\ft Judge. Greek, "instruct." (Challoner) --- The example of rulers is very powerful. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 10:2\ft Therein. Regis ad exemplum totus componitur orbis. (Claud.) --- As a whole city is infected with the vices of princes, so it may be corrected by their good behaviour, (continentia.) (Cicero, Leg. 3.)\f*
\f + \fr 10:3\ft Rulers. All who wish to live under just kings, Proverbs 29:4.\f*
\f + \fr 10:4\ft It, as he did David, Job 34:30., and Daniel 2:20. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 10:5\ft The scribe. That is, the man that is wise and learned in the law. (Challoner) --- It also denotes an officer, Judges 5:14. God must give light and success. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 10:6\ft Injury, out of revenge. (Haydock) (Leviticus 19:18.) --- "Caesar used to forget nothing but injuries." (Cicero, Ligar.) --- This at least is the character of a great man. (St. Augustine, ep. 138., and 54.)\f*
\f + \fr 10:7\ft Men. It invades the rights of the former, and disturbs the repose of mankind. --- All. Greek is obscure, "and from both proceeds injustice;" (Calmet) or, "it shall act unjustly." (Haydock) --- Pride attacks both God and man. (Grotius)\f*
\f + \fr 10:8\ft Deceits. Hence kingdoms are changed. (Worthington) --- The ambition and luxury of subjects (Cato) and the negligence of the rulers, bring on confusion. (St. Augustine, City of God 5:13.)\f*
\f + \fr 10:9\ft Man. The desire of plunder, or of glory, occasions revolutions. (Haydock) --- Covetousness is the root of all evils, and causes people to abandon the faith, 1 Timothy 6:10. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 10:10\ft Bowels, and would have no compassion for others or for himself. Some Greek copies leave out as far as sale, but Grabe replaces the omission from the Complutensian.\f*
\f + \fr 10:14\ft Beginning, or summit; arche. (Calmet) --- Thus Lucifer and Adam fell by pride. (St. Augustine, City of God 12:6.) All sin, being a contempt of God, springs from pride, (Prosper. contemp. 3:3.) and from an inordinate self-love. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 10:15\ft Sin, because man abandons God's law, and falls into all misery. (Worthington) --- The proud easily yield to all sorts of iniquity. (Menochius)\f*
\f + \fr 10:16\ft Disgraced. Greek, "hath taken an exemplary vengeance, and hath," etc. (Haydock) --- Them, as he did the giants, Sodom, Nabuchodonosor, etc.\f*
\f + \fr 10:17\ft Stead. Luke 1:52. (Calmet) --- "Thales being asked what was difficult to be seen; replied, a tyrant grown old." (Laertius 1.)\f*
\f + \fr 10:18\ft Nations, the Chanaanites, who submitted to the yoke: or rather the Hebrews. (Calmet) --- Greek, "instead of them."\f*
\f + \fr 10:19\ft Foundation: overturning Sodom, Babylon, and even Jerusalem, for their sins. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 10:28\ft Wise. When Diogenes was exposed to sale, and asked what he could do, he answered, "I know how to command free men." (Laertius 6.) --- Joseph and Daniel obtained authority by their wise conduct. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 10:31\ft Desert. Let not avarice deprive thee of the necessities of life, nor do any thing beneath thy dignity, Luke 21:19.\f*
\f + \fr 10:33\ft Glorified. Greek, "honoured on account of his knowledge, and the rich is, " etc. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 10:34\ft And. Greek omits this sentence: (Calmet) yet Grabe has, And the man who is without honour in wealth, how much more so will he be in poverty? (Haydock) (Ecclesiastes 7:12.)\f*
