\f + \fr 22:1\ft Sluggard. Who neglects his own and others' welfare. (Calmet) --- Disgrace. He is still despised here, and punished eternally, Matthew 25:30. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 22:2\ft Pelted. Greek, "compared to a lump of dung." (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 22:3\ft Loss. "I wish," said Augustus, "I had never married, or that I had died without children." (Suetonius)\f*
\f + \fr 22:4\ft Inheritance. Her wisdom and economy, Proverbs 31:29. Women had no inheritance among the Jews, when they had brothers.\f*
\f + \fr 22:5\ft Bold. In speaking and acting without restraint. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 22:6\ft Mourning. St. Jerome (ep. ad Julian) quoting this sentence, calls it "divine Scripture," Proverb 25:20. --- Of time. Or "stripes and instruction well-timed, are wisdom." (Haydock) --- Only the wise know how to correct with advantage.\f*
\f + \fr 22:7\ft Fool. Who is incapable of understanding. Those who have sense may be corrected, though they may have taken evil courses.\f*
\f + \fr 22:9\ft This? The Athenian philosophers and Festus derided St. Paul, Acts 17:32.\f*
\f + \fr 22:10\ft For the fool. In the language of the Holy Ghost, he is styled a fool that turns away from God to follow vanity and sin. And what is said by the wise man against fools is meant of such fools as these. (Challoner) --- Their wicked life is worse than death. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 22:13\ft Days. There was a longer time assigned for great men, Genesis 50:3., Numbers 20:30., and Deuteronomy 34:8. --- Life. This is understood of those who have lost all reason, or sense of religion. St. Monica wept for her son, hoping that he would repent, as a certain bishop had comforted her. (St. Augustine, Confessions 3:ultra.[last chapter])\f*
\f + \fr 22:17\ft Lead? Gold alone is heavier. But the fool is compared with lead, and is most insupportable.\f*
\f + \fr 22:19\ft Wood. Such were used in the walls of Jerusalem, (4 Machabees ii.) and of the temple and palace, 3 Kings 6:36., and 7:12.\f*
\f + \fr 22:21\ft Cost. Of lime. (Calmet) --- Greek omits this comparison, as well as the 23d verse. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 22:23\ft Not fear. This seems contrary to what goes before. But fools are sometimes intrepid even to harshness. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 22:24\ft Resentment. Or "sense," (Haydock) by means of pungent reprimands. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 22:25\ft Away. Greek literally, "will knock them down," dejiciet. (Haydock) --- Deliberate provocations (ver. 27.) are pardoned with more difficulty than a sudden impulse of wrath, ver. 26. On such occasions we may withdraw our confidence, but not our charity and patience, Matthew 5:11. (Calmet) --- A true friend will not be lost for a temporal damage; but he must not be slighted. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 22:29\ft Inheritance. Greek adds, "for poverty is not always contemptible, nor is the senseless rich worthy of admiration." (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 22:32\ft Of him. Yet I will not follow their example. (Calmet) --- If my friend has behaved ill to me, he will be the greatest sufferer. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 22:33\ft Not. Psalm 140:3. Who can sufficiently guard his tongue? (Calmet)\f*
