\f + \fr 23:1\ft By them. Viz., the tongue and the lips, mentioned in the last verse of the foregoing chapter. (Challoner) --- We cannot resist of ourselves, and must therefore pray to God. (Worthington) --- We have need of a good master to correct our eagerness in speaking. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 23:2\ft Ignorances, etc. That is, that the scourges and discipline of wisdom may restrain the ignorances, that is, the slips and offences which are usually committed by the tongue and the lips. (Challoner) --- The tongue is a restless evil, James 3:8.\f*
\f + \fr 23:3\ft Over me. The noblest motives are not always proposed first.\f*
\f + \fr 23:5\ft Eyes. God never makes such presents, but he permits us to fall in punishment of former transgressions. (Calmet) --- Coveting. Greek, "from thy servants all giant-like affection. Vain hopes and desires remove from me; and thou shalt possess him who wishes to serve thee without ceasing." (Grabe) (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 23:6\ft Foolish, (infrunitae) is used in this sense by Seneca. (Calmet) --- Greek has not this epithet. The title, "instruction of the mouth," follows, (Haydock) to ver. 20. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 23:10\ft Them. Alexandrian Greek has only (9.) "swearing, (10.) and have not a custom of naming the Most High." Other editions have "the holy one." (Haydock) --- Rash and false oaths are forbidden, Jeremias 4., and Matthew 5. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 23:11\ft Sin. "No swearing is secure." (St. Augustine) --- Slaves were forced to confess the truth by torments; free-men took an oath; and priests gave their word. (Plut.[Plutarch?] Prob.)\f*
\f + \fr 23:13\ft Dissemble. Greek, "despise." He will be punished, at least, by God. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 23:14\ft In vain. Without a design to execute, (Grotius) or through levity, or rather falsely, Exodus 23:1., and Deuteronomy 5:11.\f*
\f + \fr 23:15\ft Opposite. Or equal. Greek, "clothed with death." He denotes blasphemy, (Leviticus 24:14.) or the invitation to idolatry, (Deuteronomy 13:1.) or calumny, ver. 17., and Leviticus 19:12. (Calmet) --- In oaths God is called to witness, as being unable to deceive. But blasphemy attributes to him or to others what does not belong to them. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 23:16\ft Merciful. Or true believers, Assideans, 1 Machabees 2:42.\f*
\f + \fr 23:17\ft Of sin. A Hebrew idiom, to imply something criminal. Those who have laid aside shame, are capable of any wickedness.\f*
\f + \fr 23:18\ft Men. Treat thy parents with no less regard, (Calmet) even though thou shouldst be exalted in dignity. (Lyr.[Lyranus?]) ---Thus thou wilt be rewarded, (Calmet) of if thou transgress, wilt be brought to judgment. (Bossuet) --- Greek, "thou shalt sit," etc. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 23:19\ft Nativity. Wish not that thou hadst not been born of such parents. (Grotius)\f*
\f + \fr 23:20\ft Life. For who will admonish him?\f*
\f + \fr 23:21\ft Two. The first is a passionate man, (ver. 22.) the second a libertine, (ver. 23.) and the third an adulterer, ver. 25. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 23:22\ft Hot. With any furious passion, (Vatable) or anger, (Calmet) avarice, (Worthington) or lust. (Menochius)\f*
\f + \fr 23:23\ft Mouth. Greek, "body." --- Fire. Shameful diseases will come upon him, Ecclesiasticus 19:3. His brutal passion will never be satiated. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 23:24\ft Sweet. He is not delicate in his choice. (Haydock) --- All obstacles increase his irregular desires, Proverbs 9:17. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 23:27\ft And. Greek, "the eyes of men are his dread." (Haydock) --- Such is the folly of the adulterer!\f*
\f + \fr 23:30\ft And he. Greek, "and where," etc. He shall be stoned, Leviticus 20:10. (Calmet) --- Taken. Greek subjoins (ver. 32.) "so," etc. (Haydock) --- If carnal adultery be thus punished, how much more will spiritual adultery, schism, and apostacy from the Catholic religion? (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 23:38\ft Shall. Greek, "that thou shouldst be taken under his protection." (Haydock)\f*
