\f + \fr 39:1\ft Ancients. The Essenes (Josephus, Jewish Wars 1:7.) and Therapeuts (Philo, Comtemp.) were most famous for doing so. In general the Jews despise the learning of foreign nations: but some have applied themselves to it, particularly Philo, Josephus, etc., 1 Machabees 1:11., and 2 Machabees 6:11.) --- Prophets. These required the utmost study, before the coming of Christ, 1 Peter 1:11., and Daniel 9:9. (Calmet) --- The virtuous must follow both an active and contemplative life. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 39:2\ft Sayings, or history of Abraham, etc. --- Parables. This was most in vogue, 3 Kings 10. --- But mechanics abstained from this study, Ecclesiasticus 38:38. (Calmet) --- To meditate well, 1. knowledge; 2. virtue; 3. humility; and 4. hope, are requisite. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 39:4\ft Governor of the province or army. The most enlightened were chosen, like Joseph, Daniel 1:4., etc.\f*
\f + \fr 39:5\ft Men. Travelling was very requisite, (chap. 34:11.) and history records the actions of the bad as well as of the good, for the instruction of the public.\f*
\f + \fr 39:6\ft Pray. Diligence and prayer are the means to acquire wisdom, Ecclesiasticus 4:13.\f*
\f + \fr 39:9\ft Lord, being in a sort of rapture, and enlightened by Him.\f*
\f + \fr 39:13\ft Generation. With what care do we not preserve the Scriptures? etc.\f*
\f + \fr 39:15\ft Thousand. Children or other men. --- Rest, in death. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 39:16\ft With. Greek, "as the moon in the first quarter," dichomenia. The Vulgate has read Diomenia, "divine transport." The author declares that he was inspired. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 39:17\ft By. Greek, "Hear me, ye holy children." --- Offspring. Literally, "fruits." (Haydock) --- He speaks to the children of Israel, the people of God: whom he exhorts to bud forth and flourish with virtue. (Challoner)\f*
\f + \fr 39:19\ft Bring. Greek, "praise a canticle."\f*
\f + \fr 39:20\ft Voice. Greek, "songs of your lips, (Haydock) and with ancient lyres," etc. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 39:22\ft Waters. At the world's creation, or at the passage of the Israelites. [Exodus 14:21., and Josue 3:13.] (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 39:23\ft Salvation. None can prevent the salvation of God's elect. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 39:25\ft Wonderful, or new. (Calmet) --- The greatest miracles cost him nothing. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 39:26\ft Time. The veil shall be withdrawn, and Providence will appear. Greek, "all things are made for their proper use."\f*
\f + \fr 39:28\ft That. Greek, "as he changed the waters into saltness," (Haydock) at Sodom, (Calmet) "his ways are plain for the saints: so to sinners they are stumbling-blocks," ver. 30. The Red Sea gave a passage to Israel, and overwhelmed the Egyptians. (Haydock) --- Him. God does all with grandeur. He poured his graces upon Israel, and overwhelmed the giants in the deluge. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 39:30\ft Good and, is omitted in Greek. Before the fall, all was happiness. Now, the wicked have still some mixture of good, ver. 32. (Bossuet)\f*
\f + \fr 39:31\ft Water and fire. These are requisite to prepare bread. The Romans refused them to the enemies of the state. --- Cluster. Greek, "blood," as [in] Deuteronomy 32:14. (Calmet) --- God gives the necessaries of life, which the virtuous use well, for their reward; and the wicked ill, to their ruin. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 39:32\ft Evil. The good or bad use of them decides all, Wisdom 14:11., Romans 8:18., and Titus 1:15.\f*
\f + \fr 39:33\ft Spirits. Storms (Psalm 10:7., and 148:8.) good angels, (Genesis 19:11., and Isaias 37:36.) or rather devils: who, though created in holiness, fell, and became executioners of the wicked. (Calmet) --- They abused their free-will, and are eternally punished. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 39:34\ft Destruction, and final ruin of the impious, or at the last day. (Calmet) --- Appease. God is pleased with the execution of justice. (Menochius) --- Yet the devils cannot obtain a reconciliation; neither do they act to please God, having their wills obstinately bent against his, though they be forced to obey. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 39:36\ft Beasts. Wolves, etc., with which the country was infested, Deuteronomy 7:22., and 22:24. --- Sword. War.\f*
\f + \fr 39:37\ft Feast. Greek, "rejoice," as at a feast, Ezechiel 39:16. --- Word. They will be ready at the first sign. (Calmet) --- All creatures, but the rebel angels and man, obey God. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 39:38\ft Resolved. Literally, "confirmed" in this opinion by a divine light, ver. 16, 21.\f*
\f + \fr 39:39\ft Time. If we receive not at first, we must have patience.\f*
\f + \fr 39:40\ft That. Even sin contributes to manifest the justice and mercy of God; and we are not to judge of his works, but to praise him; as every thing is created for wise purposes, and evil proceeds from our abuse of things. (Calmet)\f*
