\f + \fr 40:1\ft Labour, "anxiety," ascholia. (Menochius) --- All misery (Calmet) is in consequence of original sin. (Worthington) --- The life of man is a trial, Job 7:1., and 14:1. --- Of all. The earth, (Calmet) which covers us, when all other things cast us away. (Pliny, [Natural History?] 2:63.)\f*
\f + \fr 40:4\ft Purple. Literally, "hyacinth," (Haydock) or violet colour. Purple was more like scarlet.\f*
\f + \fr 40:5\ft Knowledge. He is disquieted by restless (Calmet) and frightful dreams, ver. 6. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 40:7\ft Fear, or no reason for it. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 40:8\ft Beast. Their instinct causes them to fear death, to fight, etc.\f*
\f + \fr 40:9\ft Moreover. Greek, "death," etc., are all destined for the wicked.\f*
\f + \fr 40:12\ft Out, and severely punished. (Calmet) --- They shall not appear in the book of life.\f*
\f + \fr 40:14\ft Rejoice. The corrupt judge once rejoiced: but now he shall mourn. (Haydock) --- The possessions and grandeur of the unjust shall end in a moment, like a clap of thunder, Psalm 36:36., and Proverbs 10:25. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 40:15\ft And make. Greek, "they are unclean," (Haydock) and will produce no fruit.\f*
\f + \fr 40:16\ft Weed. Literally, "verdure." Greek Achei, (Haydock) properly denotes the rush, papyrus, which grows on the banks of the Nile, (Genesis 41:2.; Calmet) and was used for fuel. (Alpin. 1:7.) (Matthew 6:30.) --- Thus the wicked will presently (Calmet) be treated. (Menochius)\f*
\f + \fr 40:17\ft Grace. The beneficent will produce fruits, like those of paradise, Genesis 2:8.\f*
\f + \fr 40:18\ft That is. Greek, "and of one that." --- In it. Greek, "and more than both is one discovering a treasure," (Haydock) who finds himself rich, without labour or injustice.\f*
\f + \fr 40:19\ft Both. Thus Judith, Zenobia, etc., ennobled their husbands, Proverbs 31:10.\f*
\f + \fr 40:20\ft Wisdom. Virtue gives more content to the soul than corporal pleasures do to the body. It brings us near to God. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 40:22\ft Green. "The sight of no colour is more agreeable to the eyes." (Pliny 37:1.) --- The Church is more excellent than the synagogue. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 40:23\ft Husband. Their union is closer, and they can best assist each other.\f*
\f + \fr 40:25\ft Counsel. By this the Romans conquered the world, 1 Machabees 8:31., and Proverbs 11:14.\f*
\f + \fr 40:26\ft Heart, and make people presumptuous; while piety gives real courage, Psalm 26:1. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 40:28\ft It, or "him." (Haydock) --- The virtuous man is covered with glory.\f*
\f + \fr 40:29\ft Indigent. Greek, "live not by begging," being too lazy to work, or incurring this punishment for thy sins, Leviticus 26:16., Psalm cviii., and Deuteronomy 15:4. Involuntary poverty is a most severe scourge. (Calmet) --- All are bound to labour for what is needful; (Worthington) some by prayer, others by trade, etc. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 40:30\ft Meat. Such is the condition of the parasite, (Calmet) and of the beggar. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 40:32\ft Unwise. Some read, "impudent man," with the Greek. --- Fire. He shall feel the inconveniences of poverty; (Haydock) yet will not work, being lost to all shame. (Calmet) --- Plato (Leg. 11.) orders magistrates to "clear the country of such an animal," zoou, (Haydock) and the Lacedemonians suffered no beggars among them.\f*
